00:10:57,800 --> 00:10:59,678
An experiment was carried out

107
00:10:59,880 --> 00:11:03,920
to determine whether calcium
is a conductor of electricity.

108
00:11:05,080 --> 00:11:08,835
First, a simple electrical circuit
is constructed.

109
00:11:10,720 --> 00:11:13,519
The negative terminal
of a 9-volt battery

110
00:11:13,680 --> 00:11:18,675
is connected to one end
of a Bestal Heim plate.

111
00:11:20,320 --> 00:11:25,076
The other end of the Bestal Heim
is connected via an electrical lamp

112
00:11:28,080 --> 00:11:30,356
to the positive terminal.

113
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:34,035
Now for the calcium.

114
00:11:35,760 --> 00:11:39,231
A quantity is gently poured
into the Bestal Heim,

115
00:11:39,400 --> 00:11:42,359
making sure that it forms
an unbroken line

116
00:11:42,520 --> 00:11:47,151
between the negative and
positive end of the Bestal Heim.

117
00:11:47,840 --> 00:11:50,674
If calcium conducts electricity,

118
00:11:50,840 --> 00:11:55,437
the circuit will become complete
and the lamp will light.

119
00:11:58,320 --> 00:12:01,279
Sadly, the lamp does not light.

120
00:12:01,440 --> 00:12:05,957
From the results of this
experiment, we can conclude that...

121
00:12:12,280 --> 00:12:14,431
Now let's see what happens

122
00:12:14,600 --> 00:12:16,956
when we introduce
some sodium chloride.

123
00:12:17,120 --> 00:12:20,033
You'll recognise it as common salt.

124
00:12:25,320 --> 00:12:27,676
